is sort of what we'll be talking about.

44
00:02:23,116 --> 00:02:24,457
So overt randomness in games.

45
00:02:24,858 --> 00:02:26,499
This is actually easy to see.

46
00:02:26,579 --> 00:02:27,520
It's easy to define.

47
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:28,440
It happens a lot.

48
00:02:29,261 --> 00:02:31,743
You can have dice, cards, random number generators.

49
00:02:32,083 --> 00:02:34,685
And that's clearly going to add a degree of randomness

50
00:02:34,705 --> 00:02:35,106
to your game.

51
00:02:37,063 --> 00:02:38,584
Some things that may be less clear

52
00:02:39,265 --> 00:02:42,107
are game-theoretic randomness that

53
00:02:42,167 --> 00:02:49,553
comes from, say, simultaneous decisions, other players,

54
00:02:49,834 --> 00:02:50,334
politics.

55
00:02:51,215 --> 00:02:53,276
There's a lot of other ways besides sort

56
00:02:53,296 --> 00:02:54,437
of overt randomness.

57
00:02:57,260 --> 00:02:58,961
And then, of course, there's physical and mental

58
00:02:58,981 --> 00:02:59,522
limitations.

59
00:03:00,983 --> 00:03:01,483
Your memory.

60
00:03:04,931 --> 00:03:06,793
Your accuracy, throwing darts at a dartboard,

61
00:03:07,194 --> 00:03:08,035
that's clearly random.

62
00:03:08,876 --> 00:03:10,818
Again, it's not completely random,

63
00:03:11,559 --> 00:03:13,541
but for all practical purposes, it's

64
00:03:13,681 --> 00:03:16,805
random within a certain set of parameters.

65
00:03:16,845 --> 00:03:19,408
Your speed, your strength, these are the sorts of things

66
00:03:19,428 --> 00:03:21,510
that create randomness in games.

67
00:03:26,743 --> 00:03:30,704
way to have randomness in a game is maybe you have a simple choice between two doors.

68
00:03:31,104 --> 00:03:33,744
Door A leads to victory and door B leads to success.

69
00:03:34,665 --> 00:03:36,465
Or, sorry, failure.

70
00:03:37,605 --> 00:03:39,546
And so it's pretty clear, right?

71
00:03:39,866 --> 00:03:41,886
The ogre's behind one door and the treasure's behind the other.

72
00:03:41,906 --> 00:03:43,747
It's completely random.

73
00:03:44,147 --> 00:03:49,788
But what if you had some information about the doors that maybe you don't even see at

74
00:03:49,828 --> 00:03:51,008
first?

75
00:03:51,108 --> 00:03:56,630
There's a very complex way that you could have figured out what was behind door A.

76
00:03:57,519 --> 00:03:59,500
one door and what was behind the other.

77
00:03:59,880 --> 00:04:02,681
And this choice that was random to you,

78
00:04:03,101 --> 00:04:05,462
if you decide that you can't figure out these equations,

79
00:04:06,803 --> 00:04:07,483
is it really random?

80
00:04:07,524 --> 00:04:08,784
Is it really randomness in the game?

81
00:04:08,884 --> 00:04:09,865
Or is it a matter of skill?

82
00:04:10,505 --> 00:04:12,626
So oftentimes, when you ask people

83
00:04:13,286 --> 00:04:15,547
to name a game that has no luck in it,

84
00:04:16,828 --> 00:04:19,330
chess is the first thing that pops up.

85
00:04:20,230 --> 00:04:21,691
Because there's no overt elements.

86
00:04:21,791 --> 00:04:23,532
There's no hidden decisions.

87
00:04:25,193 --> 00:04:28,195
And so it seems, it feels like, this

88
00:04:28,215 --> 00:04:32,437
should be a game where it's a game of pure skill.

89
00:04:33,097 --> 00:04:37,220
My business partner Richard has often said, oh, maybe one day

90
00:04:37,260 --> 00:04:38,941
he'll play Garry Kasparov at chess.

91
00:04:39,201 --> 00:04:42,623
And to sort of prove that there's randomness in chess,

92
00:04:43,083 --> 00:04:44,023
he'll just play randomly.

93
00:04:45,617 --> 00:04:49,337
and win. And it's clear that he can do this.

94
00:04:50,658 --> 00:04:53,438
Garry Kasparov has not won every chess game he's ever played

95
00:04:54,058 --> 00:04:56,379
and as long as there is some set of moves

96
00:04:57,059 --> 00:05:00,340
that will lead to victory against him,

97
00:05:00,740 --> 00:05:04,020
Richard can stumble upon it. Unfortunately,

98
00:05:04,520 --> 00:05:08,321
his chances are better winning the New York State Lottery 15 times in a row.

99
00:05:08,861 --> 00:05:11,342
So he shouldn't go betting a lot of money on

100
00:05:13,505 --> 00:05:14,446
playing against Gary.

101
00:05:14,486 --> 00:05:18,392
But the point is that there is randomness in this game,

102
00:05:19,674 --> 00:05:24,821
unless, of course, Gary has the entire move tree memorized

103
00:05:24,861 --> 00:05:27,105
in his head, and he has a response regardless

104
00:05:27,125 --> 00:05:28,246
of what that random move is.

105
00:05:31,365 --> 00:05:35,489
It feels for a game like chess that it should be pure skill.

106
00:05:36,150 --> 00:05:40,454
And sometimes we forget that chess

107
00:05:40,494 --> 00:05:42,797
is quantitatively different than tic-tac-toe.

108
00:05:42,837 --> 00:05:44,258
It's not qualitatively different.

109
00:05:44,879 --> 00:05:48,303
And tic-tac-toe is a game where you can observe people playing.

110
00:05:48,323 --> 00:05:51,126
And it's very similar to the situation of the Concealed

111
00:05:51,146 --> 00:05:52,347
Doors, where

112
00:05:54,730 --> 00:05:57,312
You and I may not experience randomness when we play it,

113
00:05:57,812 --> 00:05:58,512
but children do.

114
00:05:59,093 --> 00:06:00,734
And it's very interesting.

115
00:06:00,774 --> 00:06:05,596
There's been some reports done on this,

116
00:06:05,656 --> 00:06:06,697
of watching children play.

117
00:06:06,997 --> 00:06:10,179
And you can find that the results are mapped very

118
00:06:10,239 --> 00:06:10,739
similarly.

119
00:06:11,764 --> 00:06:15,007
in character to the results of chess players playing

120
00:06:15,027 --> 00:06:17,290
against each other, where you'll have a set of people where it's

121
00:06:17,350 --> 00:06:18,371
virtually purely random.

122
00:06:18,711 --> 00:06:19,492
Some people are better.

123
00:06:19,532 --> 00:06:21,895
They're able to see a little bit in the decision tree,

124
00:06:21,915 --> 00:06:23,056
so they're making less mistakes.

125
00:06:23,456 --> 00:06:26,720
And then some people have the game essentially solved.

126
00:06:27,961 --> 00:06:31,105
We're probably too far behind that, but the past.

127
00:06:31,705 --> 00:06:34,687
our memory of tic-tac-toe to remember when it seemed random,

128
00:06:34,707 --> 00:06:37,449
when it seemed difficult. And we had to make a guess when we

129
00:06:37,529 --> 00:06:40,130
didn't for sure know what the next best move was.

130
00:06:41,211 --> 00:06:44,593
So the point to this is that the amount of luck in a game

131
00:06:45,013 --> 00:06:46,975
is not a function of the game itself.

132
00:06:48,275 --> 00:06:50,076
It's a function of the game and the player.

133
00:06:51,097 --> 00:06:54,079
And that's something that's very important to understand.

134
00:06:55,119 --> 00:06:57,581
Let's take another pure skill game, like chess.

135
00:06:59,790 --> 00:07:03,671
It's not the most fun game, but it's still a game.

136
00:07:03,751 --> 00:07:06,472
And you've got 30 seconds to compute the 50,347,200th digit

137
00:07:06,612 --> 00:07:06,972
of pi.

138
00:07:07,052 --> 00:07:08,393
Does anyone want to play?

139
00:07:18,564 --> 00:07:19,606
And you take a guess.

140
00:07:20,146 --> 00:07:21,868
It's obvious to us.

141
00:07:21,948 --> 00:07:25,252
It may not be so obvious if we look at a game like chess,

142
00:07:25,493 --> 00:07:26,914
that there is randomness in it.

143
00:07:28,096 --> 00:07:31,520
But it is obvious that in this game, there is randomness in it

144
00:07:32,722 --> 00:07:35,044
because this is impossible to compute in the amount of time.

145
00:07:36,867 --> 00:07:37,167
However.

146
00:07:38,549 --> 00:07:40,850
Again, without changing the character of the game,

147
00:07:41,491 --> 00:07:44,292
we can say, what's the fourth digit of pi?

148
00:07:44,692 --> 00:07:46,333
And now when we're playing this game,

149
00:07:46,733 --> 00:07:49,475
this is inside the scope of the human mind

150
00:07:49,815 --> 00:07:52,236
and with a little simple memorization.

151
00:07:52,576 --> 00:07:54,577
Now all of a sudden, this game that was purely random

152
00:07:54,677 --> 00:07:56,458
has no more randomness associated with it.

153
00:07:57,959 --> 00:07:59,560
The point about this game is that.

154
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:03,639
It's not just about the game and not just about the players,

155
00:08:04,479 --> 00:08:06,520
but it actually changes over time.

156
00:08:07,381 --> 00:08:10,063
Even if you sort of understood the complexity

157
00:08:10,103 --> 00:08:12,984
of the human brain to a much higher degree

158
00:08:13,024 --> 00:08:14,565
than we'll ever understand, and even

159
00:08:14,605 --> 00:08:17,247
if you understood exactly the calculations required

160
00:08:18,848 --> 00:08:20,208
to play the previous game.

161
00:08:21,589 --> 00:08:24,590
If when you play the fourth digit of pi game in 2000 BC,

162
00:08:24,771 --> 00:08:25,611
it's purely random.

163
00:08:25,871 --> 00:08:28,352
It's no different than when those people are guessing

164
00:08:28,712 --> 00:08:30,033
the 50 millionth digit of pi.

165
00:08:30,533 --> 00:08:31,613
And when you play it around 250 BC,

166
00:08:31,694 --> 00:08:34,975
it all of a sudden becomes an incredibly skill testing game.

167
00:08:36,155 --> 00:08:38,877
Archimedes around this time starts figuring out within,

168
00:08:40,317 --> 00:08:42,178
his guess would be between three different digits.

169
00:08:43,339 --> 00:08:44,699
And now, in 2000 AD.

170
00:08:46,362 --> 00:08:52,726
or 2013, there's, again, no randomness left in the game.

171
00:08:53,426 --> 00:08:57,228
And there's a very little bit of skill, but there is some.

172
00:08:57,989 --> 00:08:59,710
And the interesting thing here is

173
00:08:59,730 --> 00:09:01,911
that you can't determine by looking at the game,

174
00:09:02,972 --> 00:09:05,253
or even the capabilities of the players,

175
00:09:05,573 --> 00:09:07,154
you can't determine how much randomness

176
00:09:07,174 --> 00:09:07,775
there is in the game.

177
00:09:07,915 --> 00:09:09,616
It's something that varies over time.

178
00:09:11,837 --> 00:09:15,397
So we think we have an idea of what these pure luck

179
00:09:15,437 --> 00:09:16,178
things mean in a game.

180
00:09:16,458 --> 00:09:18,078
But what does it mean to have skill at a game?

181
00:09:18,398 --> 00:09:22,359
Well, the dictionary definitions of skill

182
00:09:22,499 --> 00:09:23,859
are the ability to do something well.

183
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:28,160
Another way to say it is it's an intrinsic ability

184
00:09:28,260 --> 00:09:30,101
to achieve a differential outcome in a game.

185
00:09:32,061 --> 00:09:35,102
And note that all of these things, with the word well,

186
00:09:35,582 --> 00:09:36,082
or, um,

187
00:09:36,680 --> 00:09:38,622
trying to achieve one outcome over another,

188
00:09:40,204 --> 00:09:42,406
hinge on the fact that skill is essentially a comparison.

189
00:09:42,827 --> 00:09:44,909
And so the measurements of skill that we have,

190
00:09:45,209 --> 00:09:46,691
like an ELO rating system or whatever,

191
00:09:46,931 --> 00:09:49,414
are always comparisons.

192
00:09:50,235 --> 00:09:51,857
That's the best way to get at what it means

193
00:09:51,877 --> 00:09:52,678
to have skill in a game.

194
00:09:54,960 --> 00:09:55,701
When you ask people,

195
00:09:57,936 --> 00:09:59,956
Is this game more skill testing than another game?

196
00:09:59,996 --> 00:10:01,797
Does game A have more skill than game B?

197
00:10:02,197 --> 00:10:03,097
How do we measure that?

198
00:10:03,557 --> 00:10:05,378
Is there a simple way that we can do that?

199
00:10:05,758 --> 00:10:10,439
Well, when you ask, say, students in a class

200
00:10:10,699 --> 00:10:13,379
or sit around and have a discussion about it,

201
00:10:13,559 --> 00:10:17,620
some of the things that pop up are, what's

202
00:10:17,640 --> 00:10:18,800
your maximum win percentage?

203
00:10:20,401 --> 00:10:23,421
There's an intuitive thought for people that.

204
00:10:26,556 --> 00:10:29,977
If a game is very skill testing, the best player,

205
00:10:30,077 --> 00:10:32,178
a pro at that, should essentially always beat

206
00:10:32,238 --> 00:10:33,239
the worst player at the game.

207
00:10:33,579 --> 00:10:36,180
It's pretty clear if the best player in the world

208
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:38,801
has a 50% win chance against the worst player in the world,

209
00:10:38,941 --> 00:10:40,862
let's say the game is cutting for high card,

210
00:10:42,022 --> 00:10:43,983
there's no skill in the game.

211
00:10:44,643 --> 00:10:48,265
And the higher that number goes, in some sense,

212
00:10:48,705 --> 00:10:49,705
there is more skill in the game.

213
00:10:50,765 --> 00:11:10,952
Another common way of defining how much skill there is in a game, and this is actually a very interesting and effective one because it leads to, say, social structures that might develop around the game or the metagame of the game, is how many different buckets can you put people into where bucket two has a 75% chance of beating the bucket from people one?

214
00:11:11,492 --> 00:11:12,692
How long is that chain?

215
00:11:14,228 --> 00:11:17,130
The longer that is, I think almost everybody would say

216
00:11:17,171 --> 00:11:19,172
there's more skill in that game.

217
00:11:19,212 --> 00:11:22,295
The ELO rating, which I think probably most people are

218
00:11:22,335 --> 00:11:23,977
familiar with, it's the chess rating system.

219
00:11:24,017 --> 00:11:25,158
Lots of video games use it.

220
00:11:25,358 --> 00:11:26,579
It's been altered over time.

221
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:31,103
Actually can reconstruct, if the assumptions that ELO made

222
00:11:31,143 --> 00:11:36,048
are true, can reconstruct that level of the chains of skill.

223
00:11:37,629 --> 00:11:40,191
And what it does is it sort of assumes a random performance

224
00:11:40,251 --> 00:11:40,852
on people's part.

225
00:11:41,943 --> 00:11:43,704
And actually, he's pretty good at modeling

226
00:11:43,804 --> 00:11:44,585
a lot of different games.

227
00:11:45,526 --> 00:11:47,888
But the complete set of information

228
00:11:48,128 --> 00:11:51,411
is actually a much, much, much more complicated thing.

229
00:11:52,572 --> 00:11:55,254
If you really want to know how much skill there is a game,

230
00:11:55,294 --> 00:11:57,616
you would need to know the true expected win

231
00:11:57,656 --> 00:12:01,199
percentage of every single player versus every other

232
00:12:01,259 --> 00:12:02,120
player over time.

233
00:12:02,780 --> 00:12:05,042
This is not something you're going to be able to get.

234
00:12:05,102 --> 00:12:06,343
This is virtually impossible.

235
00:12:06,664 --> 00:12:09,366
And how the curves of player performance change

236
00:12:10,607 --> 00:12:12,929
is actually very interesting, because it is not

237
00:12:13,189 --> 00:12:16,191
easy to a simple linear parameterization

238
00:12:16,311 --> 00:12:17,432
of the level of skill of people.

239
00:12:19,074 --> 00:12:21,255
So you have to choose what you're

240
00:12:21,295 --> 00:12:22,577
going to measure, because you're only going

241
00:12:22,597 --> 00:12:23,557
to be able to take a slice.

242
00:12:23,777 --> 00:12:24,818
And you have to choose wisely.

243
00:12:26,562 --> 00:12:30,425
Let's take, for example, this game we'll call rando chess.

244
00:12:31,206 --> 00:12:33,228
We like to use sample games because sometimes it actually

245
00:12:33,268 --> 00:12:35,049
gets to the heart of the matter more than, say,

246
00:12:35,069 --> 00:12:36,511
a real game does.

247
00:12:37,531 --> 00:12:39,293
So you play a normal game of chess,

248
00:12:39,333 --> 00:12:40,614
and then afterward you roll a die.

249
00:12:42,055 --> 00:12:44,678
And then on a one, whoever lost the game,

250
00:12:47,380 --> 00:12:48,241
they are declared the winner.

251
00:12:51,087 --> 00:12:55,389
Well, rando chess clearly has more luck than chess does.

252
00:12:56,250 --> 00:12:57,550
But does it have less skill?

253
00:12:57,891 --> 00:13:00,452
When you think about it, any sort

254
00:13:00,492 --> 00:13:02,913
of these reasonable definitions of skill

255
00:13:02,953 --> 00:13:04,774
that you had beforehand in your intuition

256
00:13:05,234 --> 00:13:07,616
are that really, actually, it doesn't have any less skill.

